rmed, officials at Borsselle operator EPZ and elsewhere say they are in line with previous statements attributed to leading party figures both before and since the general elections on 15th May. <br>They say that, while coalition negotiations are still continuing, the clear parliamentary majority enjoyed by the three centre-right parties means that the main outlines of future government policy can already be defined relatively clearly. <br>However, they point out that final policy declarations will have to be approved by parliament following the formation of a new government, which is not expected to be finalised for at least another four to six weeks. <br>The new government is expected to be led by Jan Peter Balkenende of the CDA, whose party won 43 seats in the 150-seat parliament. The other two centre-right parties, the VVD and the LPF – founded by the flamboyant right-wing politician Pim Fortuyn, who was murdered shortly before the elections – won 24 and 26 seats respectively. <br>Meanwhile, a ruling is expected shortly in a court case brought by the outgoing government, aimed at enforcing closure of Borssele by 2003, as narrowly agreed by parliament in 1994 . <br>However, any decision to change government policy would mean that a negative outcome to the court case – from the point of view of the utility – would no longer have much practical significance. <br><br><br> <p><br><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace"><img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nuclearspace/website/images/title/title_03.jpg"> </a></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showPrevMessage?topicID=97.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showNextMessage?topicID=97.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showA